The Actuarial Society of UNSW (ASOC) is a student society which is tailored to provide support for actuarial students on campus in their challenging but rewarding experience at university. As a constituent club of the university, it is supported by Arc, the Faculty of Business and the School of Actuarial Studies.

Our vision is "To guide and facilitate a supportive, social and united actuarial student community on campus", a principle that shapes the general running and purpose of our society.
The ASOC experience can also be summed up by our motto: Aspirations, Support, Opportunities, Community, as we believe that these four words derive the essence of what students can expect from our society.

ASOC is one of the most highly regarded actuarial student societies in Australia and is also one of the most active clubs in UNSW Sydney in terms of activities and support for our members. We provide a wide range of events throughout the year, in four major areas: social; sporting; academic; and careers. These involve events such as a mentoring program, PASS classes, inter-university sporting competitions, BBQs, career seminars, camp, an annual ball and many more. We also produce a monthly publication for members and pride ourselves on developing an active network of volunteers which allows members to develop skills, get involved in campus life, and have a sense of ownership in our activities. Moreover, the latest news, snapshots and reviews of our fantastic events are published in our regular Finity Actuarial Bulletin.

We welcome all students to join ASOC and be a part of our wonderful events. It is a great chance to network with peer future actuaries. We look forward to seeing you on board in this fantastic actuarial journey with us!

Are you a student interested in expanding your knowledge of South-East Asian affairs? Or are you looking to have fun exploring different cultural foods and traditions? Well, UNSW ASEAN Society is the perfect fit for you! 

Founded in 2018, ASEANSOC serves as a community for students from all South-East Asian backgrounds and beyond to celebrate and uplift the region's shared culture and ideologies. We pride ourselves as a platform that enables passionate conversation and fresh outlooks on South-East Asia from a political, economic, and sociocultural standpoint. 

Through our events across the year, including our flagship UNSW ASEAN Conference, we aim to generate awareness on South-East Asian issues and be the force of aspirational collaboration between Australia and the region. Additionally, we aspire to highlight the beauty of South-East Asian heritage, including the variety of cuisines, folklore, and popular media it has to offer. 

Whether it be a relaxed night watching a Thai film or collaborating with a team to develop sustainable climate practices in the broader SEA region, ASEANSOC has a wide range to offer in making your university experience unique and memorable!

RunSoc Friday is our most popular run where we explore a new scenic location each week during term. With relaxed pace and distance groups, this is a great opportunity to make new friends.

We also hold a weekly "Bagels" run around Sydney Harbour. We meet at Haven Specialty Coffee, Darling Quarter every Tuesday at 7am with the choice of 8km and 12km routes.

If you're looking for something a little more intense, our head pacer holds weekly training sessions at 5:30pm on Mondays, meeting at the Village Green. With a variety of fun and challenging workouts for all levels, these sessions will help you achieve your fitness and competitive goals.

We also have our annual beginner-friendly trail running camp. You can look forward to watching the sunrise from high up in the Blue Mountains, and soaking in the spectacular Jamison Valley views during the day.

Come along to a run to see what we're all about!

clubDetails.Description: The Catholic Asian Student Society (CASS), as the name suggests, is a Catholic based society that aims to help people learn more about the Catholic faith and to help members find fellowship and formation in their faith. On campus, CASS holds faith sharings / discussions every week and off campus, holds inter-uni events with USYD, UTS and MACQ, as well as weekly trips to the Matthew Talbot Hostel to help out with their Soup Kitchen. Going to these events and being a part of CASS is a great way develop lifelong friendships and most of all, develop a deeper relationship with God. Welcome! We are a society dedicated to creating a home for Catholics and non-Catholics alike to grow in friendship, learn about our Catholic faith and ultimately grow in relationship with God at UNSW. We have Mass celebrated for us everyday on campus, bible groups (both student and staff-led), volunteering opportunities and have regular social events to get to meet other students with similar interests.

We are the Warriors, members of UNSW's Cheer and Dance Society!
We have a full calendar of social events, dance and cheer classes every year starting in week one of term one!

We offer weekly dance classes in open and uni-only divisions in Pom, Hip Hop, Jazz and Contemporary, and cheer levels 1/2 and 3/4. With guidance from professional coaches we create routines and compete them at State and National competitions throughout the year. On top of this, we frequently run workshops, open gyms and social classes often with guest choreographers in many more dance styles such as heels, musical theatre and JFH (Jazz Funk Hip Hop). 

Our social calendar is always full, starting with a society welcome dinner and first years' initiation at the beginning of the year, plus our fundraisers such as trivia nights, then our Annual General Meeting and team end-of-year events. In the past we have done rollerblading, laser tag, bowling, karaoke and that is just to name a few. 

Being a Warrior goes far beyond being part of a competition team, we are a society that fosters friendships beyond cheer and dance and allows every member to grow and improve in their ability and confidence. We are proud to be one of the best university teams in Australia, coming off the back of 2022 Gold Coast Nationals where 9/10 teams placed in the top five, with two national champion teams!

Our National competition this year will take us to Melbourne, so stay tuned!

UNSW Cheer and Dance Society ultimately creates a welcoming, team-based environment and we are so proud to be Warriors, on and off the competition floor. 

At the end of every training and before every competition, we gather in a circle for our signature chant, and that is....

1,2, Warriors, WOO!!

clubDetails.Description:
The UNSW Chess Club is Australia's largest university chess club. We foster a welcoming and supportive community for chess players of all levels and offer frequent social and competitive events, in-person and online, for all members and visitors.

Through competing in the Australian Universities Chess League, we have become regarded as one of the strongest university chess clubs in Australia, with our members ranging from absolute beginners to winners of major tournaments including the Australian Junior Chess Championships and NSW Chess Championships.

We also boast a large and inclusive community of chess improvers of all levels, from learning how the pieces move to analysing the intricacies of grandmaster play. Our community on Discord is committed to supporting all members in their advancement from patzer to grandmaster.

Membership and most events are free. Our events range from casual events for beginners to learn the immortal game together to competitive tournaments featuring our strongest players. We aim to run about four events each term on campus, which include our beloved Blitzfriending event where new UNSW students make friends over casual games, and our exciting End of Term Tournaments where our strongest players battle it out for glory. We also run weekly online fun tournaments where we play chess with a twist - such as with unique rules or different starting positions. 

We invite you to join the UNSW Chess Club and become a part of our rich history and vibrant community. Together, we can continue to promote the game of chess and build a stronger community of players.

clubDetails.Description: The Chinese Creative Arts Club (CCAC) seeks to create a welcoming community for all Chinese art enthusiasts. Here, members can explore their talent and creativity within art, develop their skills and meet fellow talented artists who share the same passions and interests.\nWe are aiming to provide entertaining and informative activities such as workshops, presentations, and casual social events, to engage a friendly and respectful community for like-minded Chinese art enthusiasts, hobbyists, and professionals-to-be among UNSW students. Weekly, we run a boardgames activity to engage our community in a casual and friendly manner after class on Fridays, and we have frequent arts and crafts workshops such as scarf-knitting, clay-making, and many more. We also host outdoor photography meet-up events as well as career-related activities for those who wish to pursue arts more professionally. We wish to help UNSW students, especially Chinese art students to cultivate a sense of belonging, inspire, and support them to pursue their future dreams by improving upon their skills and abilities through joining our community. So don't hesitate! Become our member and meet our wonderful team!!

The Chinese Musician Society aims at providing opportunities for Chinese background students who are interested in music and other creative arts areas to meet, know and learn from each other. We also hold competitions to encourage society members to improve their skills. It is responsible for spreading spirits of traditional Chinese musical instruments to UNSW students.

Our events provide a great social opportunity for those who are willing to meet people and make new friends. We have a diverse range of members, which mainly consists of students from Mainland China, Hong Kong, Taiwan, South Eastern Asia, and local Australian Chinese students. As a non-profit student organisation, we aim to help students in both academic and social life in Sydney. We devote our best efforts to serve as a uniting force for students through which to promote a better understanding and identification with the Chinese culture and heritage. We welcome anyone who may be interested in Chinese culture or would simply like connect with others.

CHYK (Chinmaya Yuva Kendra) is a UNSW student society that focuses on something so simple, yet so often overlooked - OURSELVES. We aim towards more happiness, dynamism and spiritual learning. We partner with CHYK Sydney, the youth wing of Chinmaya Mission, for many of our activities. How much do we truly know about ourselves? Do we know our own dynamic potential and the power of our own ability? Do we know how to channel our minds towards achieving great success? Do we know why we sometimes feel so angry, frightened, or sad? Do we know how we can be happy and peaceful at all times? CHYK is a meeting place for young minds seeking a greater awareness and understanding of themselves and the world around them. By questions, reflection, and discussion, we seek to empower ourselves and our lives. The wealth hidden in our religion and culture help us grow beyond our limitations, so that we can face the challenges of life with purpose, confidence, and inspiration. Chyks are not those who are not content to sit back and watch, but we want to make a difference in the world, through right thinking and right actions. Chinmaya Mission is a global spiritual organisation that was founded in 1953 by devotees of Swami Chinmayananda in India. They formed the nucleus of a movement of spiritual renaissance that now encompasses a wide range of spiritual, educational and charitable activities, ennobling the lives of thousands in India and outside its shores.

CEVSOC, the school-affiliated UNSW Civil and Environmental Eng society, run by our passionate undergraduate students. 

Our aim is to help guide you in the right direction so that you can make the most of your time at university and leave with long-lasting memories that you will cherish for life. We do this by: 
\xe2\x80\xa2 Delivering a diverse range of high-quality events and resources for social, academic, and professional development;
\xe2\x80\xa2 Creating a supportive community of like-minded individuals; and

clubDetails.Description: If you're a UNSW Co-op student, then this is your society! The UNSW Co-op Society, or Co-opSoc, is dedicated to providing a social and support network to all UNSW Co-op Scholars. Our numerous events throughout the year allow Co-ops to create friendships and professional networks that guide them through their personal and academic lives both now and in the future. Co-opSoc is an integral part of a Co-op scholar's campus life with a social calendar created to meet their needs (and wants!). The Co-opSoc Camp and Ball is an annual necessity, and leadership challenges and mixers will give everyone the opportunity to catch up with the old whilst making new friends. Colombo House is a residential college for both undergraduate and postgraduate students, and members must be residents of the college. Prior to COVID-19 restrictions, BBQs, movie, trivia and talent nights, social sporting opportunities, food fairs, cultural performances, cooking classes, as well as regular outings exploring everything Sydney has to offer were activities that allowed Colombo House to build a strong sense of community among its residents. With over 35 nationalities represented from all corners of the globe, Colombo House is a thriving multicultural community with a focus on international activities and events. In fact, the Colombo International Food Festival is one of the most delicious events of the year!

The UNSW Commerce (International) Society is here to enrich the university lives of all current students of the Bachelor of Commerce (International) program and all students seeking a global mindset through the provision of opportunities for personal and professional development.

We support Christian child development and are advocates for children living in extreme poverty through partnership with Compassion Australia and their Child Sponsorship Program. We do this through our Compassion UNSW Group Sponsorship Program and run events to raise awareness and funds in support of seeing children in poverty become responsible and fulfilled Christian adults who bring positive change in their communities.

DRU is a team of multi-disciplinary engineering students who are working on humanitarian projects in partnership with the Love Mercy Foundation (LMF) and Northern Ugandan communities, aimed at fostering sustainable development through drought-resilient agriculture. DRU has been continuing to operate as part of the Student Projects pillar of UNSW?s ChallENG program since 2019. DRU adds value through the research and development of human-centered designs based on water supply reliability, water demand reduction, and weather data analysis. The 3 main projects that the DRU team are currently working on include: - Solar-Powered UV-C water purification systems for rainwater tanks. The team is currently working in partnership with UNSW Professors and Gulu University to test different prototypes to achieve the most sustainable and efficient system. Targeted SDG?s = 3. Good Health and Well-being, 6. Clean water and sanitation, - Research into more efficient agricultural and irrigation practices for more successful harvesting. Targeted SGD?s = 1. No Poverty, 2. Zero Hunger, 5. Gender Equality, 12. Responsible Consumption and Production - Weather data analysis - In December 2019, the DRU team travelled to Uganda to install 2 solar-powered weather stations with the aim of analysing rainfall patterns to provide LMF with the opportunity to educate the Ugandan women (breadwinners for their families) on farming with consideration of rain to minimise the impacts of drought and erratic climate patterns. Targeted SGD?s = 2. Zero Hunger, 12. Responsible Consumption and Production DRU is a student-led project with Dr Andrew Dansie (Senior Lecturer in Humanitarian Engineering) being our Academic Advisor. DRU is a long-term project with opportunities to travel to Uganda.

Engineers Without Borders (EWB) Australia is a non-profit humanitarian organisation that aims to harness the potential of engineering to create an equitable reality for the planet and its people. We aim to connect, educate and empower people through humanitarian engineering, envisioning a world where technology benefits all. 
 
The EWB UNSW university chapter focuses on raising awareness for EWB's mission by redefining engineering in the humanitarian context and inspiring the next generation of STEM changemakers. This is achieved through our flagship Youth Outreach program, which delivers hands-on design workshops to primary and high school students that introduce fundamental engineering principles. The workshops are designed to showcase various opportunities in STEM and the interdisciplinary use of human-centred design to uplift disadvantaged and/ or marginalised communities. 
 
The EWB UNSW university chapter runs social and technical events to build friendships, professional upskill and foster idea sharing among people interested in the humanitarian engineering space. Annual flagship events include the Inter-Chapter Design Corner, which takes place in Term 1 and is a 3-day hackathon where students can build their problem-solving skills and practice developing humanitarian solutions with feedback from industry, and the Humanitarian Engineering Conference (HEC) which takes place in Term 3, and is a 3-day camp that combines educational and social sessions to help students develop their understanding of the core social values fundamental to engineering and human-centered design.
 
The events are open to anyone interested in getting involved and are shared on the chapter's social media platforms throughout the year. Join now and become a critical enabler of sustainable development!

Goldstein College is a member of the UNSW Kensington Colleges. The newly renovated building located on High Street, Kensington overlooks the stunning Randwick Racecourse and provides unparalleled views of the Sydney skyline. Founded in 1964, Goldstein became to first college to offer on-campus accommodation for women at UNSW. Goldstein College was named after Philip Godfrey Goldstein who arrived in Australia in 1911, and provided generous donations to the construction of the Goldstein Dining Hall. One of the architects involved in the construction of the original building eventually went on to become the supervising architect of the Sydney Opera House. The new residence, completed in 2013, accommodates 150 students from rural, local and international students, and has won numerous architectural awards, including; Multiple Housing Award from the Australian Institute of Architects (AIA) NSW Chapter, the Horbury Hunt Commercial Award and Grand Prix at the 2014 Think Brick Awards and took honours in the 2014 National Architecture Awards. Academic support is offered to the students through an organised tutorial program, run by the colleges experienced and high achieving residential fellows across all UNSW Faculties ? notwithstanding the outstanding informal collaboration between the students themselves. Despite its strong academic standing among the other esidential Colleges, Goldstein strives to provide a balanced and holistic developmental environment for its residents. A busy sporting calendar occupies the majority of each semester, and a focus on community engagement is proliferated through a number of social justice partnerships. The strong engagement on behalf of the student population across all areas of college life is a testament to the calibre of our residents.

Welcome to IceSoc, UNSW's one and only ice skating club. Since our establishment in 2018, we have been aiming to create a fun, friendly and tight-knit community for everyone in UNSW who enjoys ice skating, regardless of skill level or experience. 

IceSoc holds Weekly Social Skating Sessions at Ice Zoo in Mascot every Thursday from 6:00 - 7:30 pm. Despite having Ice Zoo as our home rink, IceSoc also holds social skating sessions at Liverpool Ice Rink and Macquarie Ice Rink, in order to make us more accessible for members living further away from the university.

Throughout the year, IceSoc collaborates with other societies in UNSW to hold events on a bigger scale. Many of them combine ice skating with fun themes. Past examples include Disney on Ice, a costumed ice skating party and Vivid on Ice, a disco on-ice party with dance music.

If you are looking for the ultimate IceSoc experience, please ask one of our friendly execs for an IceSoc Gold Card. The Gold Card allows its holder to enjoy $5 off at every public session at Ice Zoo, our home rink until the next academic year. Note that the price of the gold card is still subject to change, so please stay tuned to our announcements if you're keen to get one!

The UNSW Labor Club is the leading club for progressive students at UNSW Sydney. We strive to build a fairer society as an active part of the labour movement.

As a club we have two main objectives:

1. To provide a forum for discussion on progressive policy and politics
2. To involve students in activism and campaigns around issues affecting young people and society, both on and off campus

2022 was a strong year for Labor. We won the Federal election and formed majority government, passing over 60 pieces of legislation for a better future before the year's end.

As part of the Labor Club, and Labor Party, you will have the opportunity to dive straight into campaigning and activism. The UNSW Labor Club is also formally affiliated with NSW Young Labor, connecting us with fellow young progressives across the state!

Despite the undeniable triumphs of last year, this March we must work towards electing a Minns Labor Government here in New South Wales.

After 12 years of Liberal National rorting, privatisation, and neglect, we need **A Fresh Start**.

And to make that happen, we need your help.

**Change starts here!**

Join the UNSW Labor Club today!

The UNSW Law Society is the peak representative body for all students in the Faculty of Law. We seek to develop UNSW Law students professionally, personally and socially, helping students achieve their aspirations on their professional and personal paths.

UNSW really does have a club for everything, and you've stumbled across one with lo-fi chill vibes and high quality good times! We're a community consisting of talented artists and music producers as well as friends that just want to chill and meet people to study or game with.

So if you're looking to find friends to study or party with, join lo-fi and vibe with us!

Want to have a chance to showcase your skills? You can sign up for our flagship mixtape project or our amazing subcommittee! So whether you're an artist who just wants to doodle with friends, an aspiring music producer or just someone who wants to study/game with friends at 3am, you'll find a second home at uni in our society!

Medical Outreachers Australia (MOA) is comprised of medical students from the University of New South Wales (UNSW). Our aim is to cultivate and develop the passion of medical students in not only the practice of medicine, but also in the provision of care for others through various humanitarian actions. Founded in 2015, Medical Outreachers Australia aspires to organize services ranging from local to international for medical students and the community. We provide an avenue for students to enrich their development as medical practitioners through academic events such as End of Course Tutorials, Meet the Medics and Peer Mentoring. Founded in 2011, the Ministry of Dance Society (MODSoc) is one of the largest university-based dance communities, with over 1,000 members from both the University of New South Wales and other tertiary educational institutes from the greater Sydney area. One Piece Society is a club dedicated to the anime/manga series 'One Piece', which has been an ongoing series that has gained a lot of popularity and accumulated many fans worldwide. It has become one of the most successful manga and TV series in the world, having broken the internet on multiple occasions and holds a key place in pop culture today. The series has broken the Guinness World record for most printed comic series by one author in 2015, and has become the 3rd highest-selling book series, behind Harry Potter and Superman. This society will be devoted to appreciating the great world-building, story, characters and pure excitement of the series, which withstands the test of time. What distinguishes us from broader societies such as AUNSW, is our specialised focus of interest in One Piece as a series, and our intentions to facilitate One Piece themed and influenced events. Furthermore, we hope to engage with members on a sentimental level, by advocating and instilling profound values and wisdom, deep-rooted in the series. Weekly read-alongs/watch-alongs, movie nights, theory-crafting and discussion calls, art sessions and get-togethers are all events very unique to the One Piece series and engage with all members, on an interpersonal level.

The UNSW Philosophy Society is a place where you can come to discuss philosophy with other passionate students. 

We hold social events (such as picnics), and Roundtable discussions (where we discuss a pre-specified philosophical topic). 

If you don't know much about philosophy, that's ok, you don't need to know anything about it. Our discussions are very beginner friendly and we provide materials that describe what each topic we discuss is about. If you want to join us, all you need is a little bit of interest. 

Philosophy covers a range of very diverse topics, from how we can know what is true with certainty, to whether God exists, to why certain acts are morally right or wrong. It can be rather difficult to define, but ultimately it asks one question: Why? 

If you've ever asked "Why?", then you're on track to becoming a philosopher. Philosophy can be thought of as the study of thinking about things deeply. We question things in philosophy. Even the most basic things. Thinking deeply about the world can be very intriguing. 

Join us, the UNSW Philosophy Society, if you want to engage in discussions about philosophy and meet like-minded people.

clubDetails.Description: PsychSoc is the constituent society which aims to engage, support, and connect all UNSW Psychology students. At PsychSoc, we are united by one core mission: to foster a sense of connectedness and community, benefiting our students by supporting their endeavours and providing opportunities to explore, enhance and work towards their goals during their University journey. We want to help you get the most out of your time in psychology, and hence aim to provide events throughout the year for the psychology student community here. Whether you are looking for social events, academic help, or career information, we?ve got you covered! Collaborating with other UNSW societies, as well as in-university and external organisations, we ensure that every psychology student will have the most enriching university experience here. PsychSoc's foundations stand upon six portfolios which innovate, organise and facilitate PsychSoc's events - Academic, Social, Relations, the Year Representatives, Wellbeing and Marketing and Media. The Academic team assists with improving the academic lifestyle and understanding of Psychology students through coding, writing, and exam workshops; whereas the Social team looks to run fun-filled events, forgetting about the stresses of university studies. The Relations portfolio helps students take the first step into connecting with the professional workplace, opening opportunities for you to talk to employers and understand what they look for in a psychology graduate. The Year Representatives bridge PsychSoc with the wider year cohorts, listening to issues, a voice to the student body, and strives to create events that introduces students to new friends in their year group. Sports and Philanthropy is all about building a student culture that remembers to share a bit of love; whether it's self-care, caring for the community or just taking the time to look after one's mental or physical health. All the events PsychSoc pulls together are only made possible by students attending them, and the Marketing and Media team shapes the event pages and marketing material for our events to ensure everyone knows what the society is up to next. The Academic Portfolio assists Psychology students with their course work, providing a range of academic resources such as workshops and Psychology core practice exams. The Social portfolio unites the Psychology student body and facilitates long-lasting bonds within a tight-knit society through inclusive, accessible and lively social events. The Relations portfolio helps students take the first step into connecting with the professional workplace, opening opportunities for you to talk to employers and understand what they look for in a psychology graduate. The Wellbeing Portfolio promotes events that are related to philanthropy and mental health with an overarching goal to improve individual wellbeing in the Psychology community. The Year Representatives are the bridge between the PsychSoc committee and the broader Psychology cohort, facilitating student engagement within each year group and being an open and accessible line of communication for students. All the events by PsychSoc are only made possible by students attending them, with the Marketing and Media team promoting events via a variety of engaging media to ensure everyone knows what the society is up to next! Overseeing all the portfolios is our executive team: the President, Vice-President Operations, the Secretary, the Arc Delegate, the Treasurer, and the Vice-President Internal. When you ask PsychSoc any questions, give us feedback or even just start a chat with us over email or Facebook, our Secretary is the one who replies. The Secretary is our go-to member and will know nearly everything and anything about our society. Our Arc Delegate keeps PsychSoc aligned with Arc, which is a student-run body that ensures all societies and clubs continue to provide services that cater to the students. The Treasurer budgets our spending so we can continue to run our events and will be the one to confirm that your payment has come through to our PsychSoc bank account. The Vice-President Internal facilitates the internal aspect of the committee, overseeing conflict resolution and bonding, and ensuring the committee members are meshing well together. The President and Vice-President work together to lead the committee, drawing from the four characteristics that stimulate the society to always work diligently to create a better UNSW. We are excited to welcome you to join our Psychology community! To keep up to date with all our events and initiatives throughout the year, make sure to do the following: 1. Join us on SpArc 2. Like and follow our FB page 3. Join your specific cohort group page on FB 4. Follow our Instagram page 5. Check out our PsychSoc website

Redback Racing is a student-led project at UNSW, under the School of Mechanical & Manufacturing Engineering and part of the ChallENG  program. We take pride in the team's commitment to the pursuit of both engineering and business excellence fulfilling our mission to equip students with knowledge and skills from beyond the classroom.

 
Our core values are personal growth, team spirit, challenge, and commitment. We promote a culture of inclusiveness to learn and grow together. The project often requires members to work under high pressure, accelerating the development of critical problem-solving abilities. Redback participates   in   two competitions annually, Formula SAE-A and FS-Sydney. FSAE-A allows students the opportunity to enhance their engineering design and project management skills. It prepares students for a career in various industries and provides the opportunity to network on a global scale. FS-Sydney is another highly rewarding experience for several students across Australia.  

 

Students have the opportunity to choose between two branches: Technical & Business. The Technical team oversees the design, manufacturing, and testing of the car. The Business team upholds the operations, finances, and branding of the team. There are opportunities throughout the team where students can diversify their skill set and meet like-minded individuals. Now transitioned to electric vehicles, we build off a remarkably successful 20-year history competing and placing podium in the combustion class - there is a lot to live up to. With the partnership of major sponsors every year, Redback Racing can develop faster and more lightweight cars to compete with in domestic and international competitions. Redback Racing is always looking for passionate new members. Prospective members can look out for our Recruitment events on our socials!

clubDetails.Description: Hello! We are a student group who are devoted to obtaining a deeper understanding of God by his Word and live as instruments of His glory. With a Reformed doctrine and an Evangelical passion, we wish to pursue the truth as well as our vocations with due excellence, and bear fruit in this world by proclaiming the Gospel with zeal and love. Club aims: 1. To reach out to the university as a ministry of the reformed evangelical movement, to encourage students to be involved in campus life, and to train students to be involved in and serve the University from a Reformed Evangelical Christian point of view. 2. To equip students with a biblical worldview that is holistic and not in different spheres. We aim not to partition the world into spiritual and secular matters, but we believe that all aspects in life is from God and by God, and as such we use this opportunity to serve him by discerning our unique, individual vocations and spare no effort to achieve them with excellence and integrity. 3. To promote the fundamental reformation principles which are: Scripture alone, Grace alone, Faith alone, Christ alone and Glory to God alone ? we wish to proclaim the truth in love as we abide by historical biblical orthodoxy and reformed theology. 4. To foster a community in Sydney?s university that reaches out to students with differing beliefs or even doubts with the Gospel message. We wish to welcome those who are not convinced of the truth of Christianity and appreciate interacting and learning about different perspectives. Our Activities: ? Weekly meetings ? Expository Bible studies ? Counseling Sessions (on demand) ? Lunch fellowships ? Public lectures/seminars: - A range of diverse topics (philosophy, theology, life applications, etc.) - International guest speakers ? A range of activities - BBQs - Movie nights - Book reviews We are hoping that people would start to realize the importance of Christian worldview in our day to day life.

Through our diverse lineup of events and initiatives, we offer many opportunities for members to get involved and immerse themselves in both academic and social pursuits. We organise events independently and in collaboration with other Singaporean societies to engage and develop members during their time in Sydney. We are keen this year to continue our tradition of hosting weekly sports events such as football and volleyball. We will be hosting regular welcome BBQs as well as our annual Camp Boomerang to give freshmen an opportunity to meet other Singaporeans and settle quickly into the new community. An important part of the Singaporean culture is the diverse range of local food delicacies which we want to share with all students at UNSW, regardless of nationality. To reaffirm our commitment to Singapore, we gather with fellow Singaporeans across all universities in Sydney to celebrate National Day Parade. We will also hosting other big events such as Amazing Race, Pot and Painting \u0026 Cruise Night to provide variety in the activities. We also collaborate with other societies in UNSW to strengthen our relationships outside the society through cultural exchange. All in all, look forward to amazing events this year and getting to appreciate Singaporean culture in home away from home!

We operate according to Social Work values of respect for diversity, a belief in social justice and the promotion of human dignity. We regularly run social and careers events on and off campus for students. Through our Facebook group, we also offer peer advice and a student perspective on doing a degree in Social Work. We advocate for and support students through our role as a liaison between the university and the Social Work cohort.

The Society of Orchestra and Pipers (SOAP) is associated with two large instrumental music ensembles at the University of New South Wales - We are the UNSW Orchestra and Wind Symphony. We regularly perform a wide range of repertoire, from classical and romantic works to contemporary and popular pieces. We invite you to attend our concerts and, if you play a wind, brass, percussion or stringed instrument, to inquire about playing with us. Welcome to SOFIA UNSW! Whether you already call yourself an Orthodox Christian or are interested in discovering the faith of the early Christians, we're delighted to have you. Join us in 2023 to learn more about Orthodoxy, get your questions answered, and develop friendships with like-minded students.

SOFIA UNSW is an Orthodox Christian fellowship that meets every week to provide a place where Orthodoxy can be experienced on-campus.

Talks are led by our chaplain, guest speakers, and fellowship members on a range of topics, including the writings of our Church Fathers, parts of the Bible, aspects of the spiritual life, and our Church's view on contemporary issues.

Throughout the year, SOFIA also organises both on and off-campus events to deepen its members' faith and friendships. Highlights during the year involve monastery day trips, volunteering events, and our annual forum, where we hear from a panel of excellent speakers on a relevant topic.

The group also enjoys casual weekly lunches to build friendships and connect with like-minded students on campus.

SOFIA is open to all, Orthodox or not, so please join us! We'd love to have you in our community, where we enjoy the presence of Christ as we learn more about Him. As Jesus himself said, "For where two or three are gathered together in My name, I am there in the midst of them." -Matthew 18:19-20

Slapping down trap cards, baits and bombs galore, grandly accusing your best friend of being a bloodthirsty werewolf, or standing shoulder to shoulder with your companions to face the monsters of your mighty Game Master! TTGSoc is devoted to sharing our love of tabletop games, whether that be board games, RPGs or TCGs.

Our community welcomes all types of players, each branch is dedicated to accommodating both players new and old, casual or competitive.

If you're interested in board games such as Catan or Betrayal, or card games such as Coup or Exploding Kittens, our Friday and Saturday in-person events are perfect for you. We bring our collection of games to UNSW and you can drop in to play for as long (or short) as you like! No idea how to play? We have people and events to help teach you! Can't come in-person? We'll be having weekly online events. 

What if you're just a dice goblin who likes to put on funny little voices? Our RPG community is huge! D&D players, new and old would love to join our commitment-free campaign. D&D too overrated for you? We'll also be holding one-shot events for other kinds of TTRPGs. Prefer to GM? We'll be holding all kinds of workshops to help cultivate your skills! And you'll always welcome to organize your own games within our community.

However, if you're more into TCGs, we're planning to hold tons of causal competitions for all types of games such as MTG or Yu-Gi-Oh, as well as events to teach lesser known ones. New to these games? We'll be holding learn-to-play events. Already there? Keep an eye out for our drafts and 'unconventional format' events! 

There's something for everyone, come check us out!

UNSW TSA is a student association for Taiwanese students as well as those interested in the Taiwanese culture. Founded in 2000, SA is a non-profit organisation that aims to expand the Taiwanese culture within Australia. UNSW TSA aims to build a community that is supportive of each other by connecting with those that share similar interests, have similar passions about the Taiwanese society including its values, music and cuisine or with those just want to meet new people.
We are a social sports club that aims to provide a unique target rifle shooting experience to members across all skill levels, from complete first-timers to seasoned veterans.

Tax Help is a free and confidential service to help you complete your tax return. Run by Arc student volunteers, the Tax Help team are not accountants, but are trained by the Australian Taxation Office and must pass an accreditation test to become Tax Help volunteers.

The UNSW Taxation and Business Law Society (TABLSoc) aims to build a like-minded and motivated community of students completing Taxation and Business law subjects or interested in pursuing a career within Taxation and Business law. TABLSoc aims to do this through the provision of academic, personal and professional development opportunities, including networking events with UNSW Alumni and industry professionals.

Looking for the best caf\xc3\xa9s on campus? Or maybe you want to meet some fellow caffeine lovers? UNSW's Tea and Coffee Society is a student-led society which aims to share our passions for tea and coffee alike and hold social functions for UNSW students. We also run Cup in Columbo, our weekly tea sessions in front of the Columbo Lecture rooms, our flagship events, High Tea and Yum Cha, and a variety of other events that will open up a world of tea and coffee for you to explore!

The Tea and Coffee Society is known for being a wholesome society, one where you can make friends, learn more about tea and coffee, and occasionally grab free beverages as a full member of our society! Feel free to follow our Instagram and Facebook pages to keep yourself updated with our events and join our Discord server to keep in touch with our members, share your beverage pics and exchange caf\xc3\xa9-style recipes. : )

To become a member (or just to check out the vibes) come visit our stall during O-Week and receive a free badge! On the 9th of February,  we will be holding a taster day with warm cuppas where you can spend some downtime with other new members and snack away with our chill executives. We hope to see you there!

Teochew Students Association (Previously UNSW Gaginang) is aimed at promoting Teochew culture and language through our events and workshops. The phrase 'gaginang' is a common term meaning 'our own people' and is used to identify people of Teochew heritage regardless of where you were born or where you come from, helping reinforce the idea that you are not alone. We hope to bring everyone across cultures together and further Teochew culture on and off campus by providing a friendly, family-like environment for people to connect.

Thai Students Society (TSS) aims to foster all Thai students at UNSW to form a community and help them in settling down in this new environment, supporting them where needed. The society provides a platform where members forms connections and bonds, with a vast array of activities held to provide opportunities for all students to get the know each other. Furthermore, the society also promotes and sustains Thai traditions and culture not only for members of the society but for the wider UNSW community to learn and experience our beautiful heritage ranging from the scrumptious foods to vibrant festivals. TSS does not only limit ourselves to connecting students within our university as we also form the Thai Student Association along with the Thai Student Societies from UTS, USYD and UW. So join our society today to learn what it's truly like to be part of the land of smiles :)

Tricking is an emerging sport that combines martial arts, gymnastics and break dancing to create an aesthetic blend of flips, kicks, and twists. UNSW Tricking Society provides training sessions and classes, built upon a community to facilitates the growth and progression of every member. We are a beginner friendly society and run weekly sessions during the UNSW teaching term on Tuesdays 2:00-4:00pm Message to Facebook page to be added to the member group chat and follow the FB and Insta page for weekly updates

We hold regular events to fulfil our only aim which is to construct strong and lasting friendships. To some, this will be an opportunity to start shaping an academic and professional network with your fellow Turkish-background peers before you head out to kick start your career. This is a great opportunity to be part of a society which we hope will establish a community that supports young Australian-Turkish undergraduates and graduates from UNSW.

While the UN(SWifties) is a new society, it's certainly not one to ignore! We're enchanted to greet a new wave of Swifties, both new and old, to our fantastic society! We're a fun-loving group of Swifties who enjoy hanging out with each other and listening to our favourite Taylor songs. Our past events have included a Midnights Album Release Party, and a picnic at Coogee Beach (where we all made Swiftie-themed friendship bracelets!), and we're excited to host similar events as the year goes on! No matter your levels of Taylor-themed knowledge, we're excited to welcome all Swifties, and we hope that you'll stay, stay, stay!

We know all too well how stressful starting university can be. The UN(SWifties) offers a fun, safe space for students to come together and de-stress - while also listening to Taylor Swift songs along the way! Our society is a great way to meet new people who love Taylor as much as you (it's nice to have a friend \xf0\x9f\xa4\x8d). If you're looking for a high-spirited society, UN(SWifties) is the place for you! Shake off the start-of-uni blues and join us for an event or two. We promise you won't be on your own, kid! As a member of our society, we'll look after you forever and always, and always welcome you to our events. 


Don't leave teardrops on our guitar - join the UN(SWifties) today - we've got a blank space for you... just write your name!:)

In 2022 we had our inaugural event, the Midnights Album Release Party, followed shortly by our final event of the year at Coogee Beach, where we made Taylor-themed friendship bracelets. Taylor Swift has gone through many eras throughout her career, thus dividing her fans on which one is arguably the best. For one of our first events of 2023, we plan to hold a 'Taylor Swift Eras Party', where all Swifties can attend dressed up as their favourite Taylor Swift era! This event would be very similar to our first event (Midnights Party), where pizza, snacks and drinks were provided, with a playlist of some of Taylor's greatest hits played in the background. This event would be the perfect opportunity for new members to get to know one another, and chat with others who also enjoy Taylor Swift's music.\n\nSome smaller-scale events we are planning to hold include a karaoke night, as well as a Taylor Swift documentary viewing night (such as the Reputation Stadium Tour Documentary). Furthermore, we plan to have a Taylor-themed trivia night to put our members to the test, and find out who is the #1 Swiftie! All these events will allow members to get closer to one another, as well as to be involved in a society that involves an artist they all enjoy!

clubDetails.Description: The University Network for Investing and Trading (UNIT) was established in 2007 and is an active student-run society. Although UNIT originally geared towards those interested in investing and trading, we have now expanded to cater to those interested in all aspects of finance. UNIT spreads across six premier Australian universities; The University of Sydney, The University of New South Wales, Macquarie University, University of Melbourne, Monash University and University of Queensland. We strive to provide financial education for novices and experts alike through our educational seminars, promote career opportunities through Facebook, weekly e-Newsletters and our website and provide professional networking opportunities for students spread across a broad range of degrees and majors. Some of our keynote events included the Citi Global Markets Challenge, Industry Insights Evening and Diversity in Finance. Over the years, UNIT has rapidly become one of the most dynamic and enthusiastically supported student bodies on campus, enjoying a strong reputation for energy and professionalism. UNIT has over 11,000 student members. The genuine value offered to members underlies our continual growth and stamps UNIT as the largest finance focused student organisations in Australia. While there are many commerce-themed societies on campus, two key aspects of UNIT's philosophy sets it distinctly apart from the pack: Firstly, UNIT's mission is pure and simple: to provide free education to students interested in trading and investing. UNIT hosts talks and presentations from industry leaders - including hedge funds, boutique funds, brokers, market-making traders and the ASX - that not only introduce students to the fundamentals of investing and trading, but expose students to industry practices not taught inside the classroom and textbook. Secondly, UNIT is student-focused. While useful careers-wise, the education provided by UNIT aims to equip students with the knowledge and confidence to start up and manage their own share portfolios and invest for life. No doubt many students begin university wondering how they too can trade shares and other instruments - UNIT aims to answer that question. As part of our student-focus, we try to cater to as many students as possible. As such UNIT also holds a variety of other events, including our inaugural Stock Pitch Challenge, workshops, coffee with a professional, poker night and round table discussions. We believe this philosophy, coupled with the unbridled enthusiasm and dedication of the UNIT team makes us a valuable contribution to student life on campus.

Do you have a passion for problem solving and want to represent UNSW on the global stage? The UNSW Consulting Club (UCC) enables you to develop your problem solving skills to solve real-world business problems through our premier education programme and participation in our International Case Competition (ICC) squad. Joining UCC means that you will be taught by experienced mentors on topics such as business strategy, competitor analysis and financial modelling. You also have the opportunity to connect with bright and like-minded students from different degrees! We send teams made up of our ICC squad members all over the globe to complete head-to-head in world-class business case competitions. Members will also be exposed to UCC's professional network of alumni from industries such as consulting, investment banking and technology so you'll be able to stand out from the crowd. If you want to make the most out of your university experience by learning from the best, making lifelong friends and by travelling around the world, be sure to join UCC. We'll see you there!
